## Files
- app/api/auth/callback/route.ts (modify)
- providers/SignedInProvider.tsx (modify)

## What to do

### 1. Callback route: early-detect error param (app/api/auth/callback/route.ts)

At the top of the GET handler, BEFORE calling `sdk.callback(searchParams)`, check if `searchParams` has an `error` param. If it does:

```ts
const error = searchParams.get("error");
if (error) {
  const description = searchParams.get("error_description") || "Authorization was cancelled";
  console.warn("OAuth authorization error:", error, description);
  // Redirect back to home with error info for the client to display
  const redirectUrl = new URL("/", config.baseUrl);
  redirectUrl.searchParams.set("auth_error", error);
  redirectUrl.searchParams.set("auth_error_description", description);
  return NextResponse.redirect(redirectUrl);
}
```

Also update the existing catch block to redirect instead of returning JSON:
```ts
catch (e) {
  console.error("Authentication failed:", e);
  const redirectUrl = new URL("/", config.baseUrl);
  redirectUrl.searchParams.set("auth_error", "callback_failed");
  redirectUrl.searchParams.set("auth_error_description", e instanceof Error ? e.message : "An unexpected error occurred");
  return NextResponse.redirect(redirectUrl);
}
```

### 2. Client-side toast in SignedInProvider (providers/SignedInProvider.tsx)

This component already wraps all pages. Add a `useEffect` that:
- Reads `auth_error` and `auth_error_description` from the URL search params (use `useSearchParams()` from next/navigation)
- If `auth_error` is present, show a toast:
  - If `auth_error === "access_denied"`: `toast.error("Login cancelled. You can try again when you're ready.")`
  - Otherwise: `toast.error(auth_error_description || "Authentication failed. Please try again.")`
- Clean the URL by calling `router.replace(pathname)` (use `usePathname()` and `useRouter()` from next/navigation) to remove the query params
- The useEffect should depend on searchParams

Note: SignedInProvider currently receives `session` as a prop from the server. The toast logic should run regardless of whether session exists (the user will have no session after a rejection). If SignedInProvider is a server component, you may need to extract the toast logic into a small client component like `AuthErrorToast` and render it inside SignedInProvider.

Import `toast` from `sonner` (already used elsewhere in the project, e.g. in components/navbar.tsx).

## Don't
- Do NOT create new pages or error boundary files
- Do NOT modify the login flow (api/auth/login, use-login-mutation, etc.)
- Do NOT add middleware
- Do NOT change the successful auth flow at all
- Do NOT install new dependencies — sonner and next/navigation are already available

## Files
- lib/atproto-branding.ts (modify)

## What to do
The PDS OAuth sign-in page has a two-panel layout on desktop. The left panel contains the H1 heading (logo/branding area) and is currently styled with a light gray background (`#f0f0f3`). Change it to dark navy `#0F2544`.

### 1. Left panel background (line ~270-274)
```css
/* Left panel styling */
.md\\:bg-slate-100,
.dark .md\\:bg-slate-100,
.md\\:dark\\:bg-slate-800 {
  background-color: #f0f0f3 !important;  /* CHANGE to #0F2544 */
}
```

### 2. Text contrast in the left panel
Since the background is now dark, any text rendered in the left panel needs to be light. The H1 text color is currently `#2b2d31` (dark). Update:

- Line ~137: `.grid h1.text-primary::after` color → `#ffffff` (or remove if task .8 replaces this with an image — but set it to white as a fallback)
- Line ~203: `main.flex.flex-col.items-center > h1.text-primary` color → `#ffffff`

Also check the `.text-primary` override at line ~317-318:
```css
.text-primary {
  color: #757780 !important;
}
```
This is a global override that affects text across ALL pages (sign-in, authorize, error). Since only the left panel is dark, scope the light text to the left panel only. Add a new rule:
```css
/* Light text for dark left panel */
.md\\:bg-slate-100 .text-primary,
.md\\:bg-slate-100 h1.text-primary {
  color: #ffffff !important;
}
```

### 3. Mobile background
On mobile the layout is single-column. The left panel content stacks on top. Check the mobile section (line ~690-727) — the `main` background is `#f8f8fa`. The mobile grid content container (`.grid.grow.content-center`) should also get the dark navy background:
```css
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  .grid.grow.content-center {
    background-color: #0F2544 !important;
    padding: 24px !important;
    border-radius: 12px !important;
  }
}
```

## Don't
- Change the right panel background (form area) — it stays light
- Change button colors or form input styling
- Modify the authorize page or error page backgrounds
- Touch any files other than lib/atproto-branding.ts

## Files
- lib/atproto-branding.ts (modify)

## What to do
The PDS branding CSS currently replaces the H1 text and submit button text with plain CSS `content: "Sign in with Certified"`. Now that the SVG assets are available, update the text replacements as follows:

### H1 heading → replace with certified-signin.svg image
The `certified-signin.svg` (334x117px) is a stylistic image containing the words 'Sign in with Certified' in a designed layout with green background section and checkmark. Use it as an image replacement for the H1 heading only.

There are 2 H1-related places to update:

**1. Sign-in page H1 (line ~134)**
```css
.grid h1.text-primary::after {
  content: "Sign in with Certified" !important;  /* CHANGE THIS */
}
```
Change to use the SVG as a background image:
```css
.grid h1.text-primary::after {
  content: "" !important;
  display: block !important;
  width: 280px !important;
  height: 98px !important;
  max-width: 100% !important;
  background-image: url('${sanitizedSigninUrl}') !important;
  background-size: contain !important;
  background-repeat: no-repeat !important;
  background-position: right center !important;
  margin-top: 8px !important;
}
```

**2. Desktop H1 variant (line ~157)**
Update the `@media (min-width: 768px)` and `@media (min-width: 1024px)` versions with larger dimensions, keeping the 334:117 (~2.85:1) aspect ratio.

### Submit button → certified-logo.svg icon + text
The submit button should show the C logo icon (`certified-logo.svg`, 39x43px) alongside the text "Sign in with Certified". This is NOT an image replacement — it's an icon + text combo.

There are 2 button-related places to update:

**3. Submit button (line ~597-606)**
```css
button[type="submit"].bg-primary {
  font-size: 0 !important;
  line-height: 0 !important;
}
button[type="submit"].bg-primary::after {
  content: "Sign in with Certified" !important;  /* CHANGE THIS */
}
```
Change to show the C logo as a ::before pseudo-element and keep the text in ::after:
```css
button[type="submit"].bg-primary {
  font-size: 0 !important;
  line-height: 0 !important;
  display: flex !important;
  align-items: center !important;
  justify-content: center !important;
  gap: 8px !important;
}
button[type="submit"].bg-primary::before {
  content: "" !important;
  display: inline-block !important;
  width: 20px !important;
  height: 22px !important;
  background-image: url('${sanitizedLogoUrl}') !important;
  background-size: contain !important;
  background-repeat: no-repeat !important;
  background-position: center !important;
  flex-shrink: 0 !important;
}
button[type="submit"].bg-primary::after {
  content: "Sign in with Certified" !important;
  font-size: 1rem !important;
  line-height: 1.5rem !important;
}
```

**4. Authenticate page button (line ~217-226)**
Same approach — ::before with C logo icon, ::after with text.

### Implementation
Add a new `signinUrl` variable alongside the existing `logoUrl`:
```typescript
const signinUrl = \`\${baseUrl}/certified-signin.svg\`;
const sanitizedSigninUrl = sanitizeUrlForCss(signinUrl);
```
The `sanitizedLogoUrl` (for certified-logo.svg) is already available from task .7 — if .7 hasn't run yet, use `\${baseUrl}/certified-logo.svg` directly and sanitize it.

## Don't
- Change any color values or non-text-replacement CSS
- Use certified-signin.svg for the buttons (that's only for the H1)
- Use certified-logo.svg for the H1 (that's only for the buttons)
- Remove the H1 text-hiding CSS (`font-size: 0`, `color: transparent`) — still needed to hide original text
- Touch any files other than lib/atproto-branding.ts
